[[ファイル:Ono jinja in Fuchu, Tokyo.JPG|thumb|right|220px|Precincts]]
'''Ono Shrine''' (おのじんじゃ) is a {{jalink|Shinto shrine|Q845945}} in {{jalink|Fuchū, Tokyo|Q208818|Fuchū}}, {{jalink|Tokyo|Q1490}}. It is a {{jalink|Shikinaisha}} {{jalink|candidate shrine|Q135022904}}. Its former rank under the {{jalink|Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534}} was {{jalink|gōsha|Q134917316}}. It is also called '''Ono-no-miya'''.

=== Overview ===
It is one of the candidates for the shikinaisha “Ono Shrine” in Tama District, {{jalink|Musashi Province|Q907398}}, listed in the {{jalink|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932}}. Another candidate is {{jalink|Ono Shrine (Tama)|Q11464224|Ono Shrine}} in {{jalink|Tama|Q213263}} (for details as a shikinaisha, see {{jalink|Ono Shrine (Tama)#History of shikinaisha “Ono Shrine”|Q11464224}}). Because this shrine is below the {{jalink|hake escarpment|Q11275384}}, it is said there came to be two shrines due to relocations caused by flooding of the {{jalink|Tama River|Q1063006}}; another view says one is the original shrine and the other a branch.

While Ono Shrine in Tama was protected by the {{jalink|Edo shogunate|Q205662}} as the {{jalink|Ichinomiya|Q1656379}} of Musashi Province, this shrine declined as reverence increased for nearby Musashi provincial {{jalink|sōsha|Q1107129}}, Rokusho-no-miya ({{jalink|Ōkunitama Shrine|Q611678}}).

In {{jalink|1873|Q7757}} (Meiji 6) it was ranked as gōsha. The shrine burned in a fire in Taishō 15, and the current buildings were rebuilt afterward.

=== Enshrined deities ===
Main deities are the following two.
* {{jalink|Ame-no-Shitaharu-no-Mikoto}}
* {{jalink|Seoritsuhime|Q13579836|Seoritsuhime-no-Mikoto}}

=== Site information ===
; Location
* {{jalink|Tokyo|Q1490}}{{jalink|Fuchū, Tokyo|Q208818|Fuchū}} Sumiyoshi-chō 3-19-3

; Access
* {{jalink|Nakagawara Station|Q4312482}} on the {{jalink|Keio Line|Q1323112}} of {{jalink|Keio Corporation|Q1332506}} (about 8 minutes on foot)

