'''Ono Shrine''' (おのじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945}} in {{ill|lt=Fuchū, Tokyo|Q208818|WD=Q208818|lt=Fuchū}}, {{ill|lt=Tokyo|Q1490|WD=Q1490}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|UNKNOWN}} {{ill|lt=candidate shrine|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904}}. Its former rank under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534}} was {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316}}. It is also called '''Ono-no-miya'''.

=== Overview ===
It is one of the candidates for the shikinaisha “Ono Shrine” in Tama District, {{ill|lt=Musashi Province|Q907398|WD=Q907398}}, listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932}}. Another candidate is {{ill|lt=Ono Shrine (Tama)|Q11464224|WD=Q11464224|lt=Ono Shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Tama|Q213263|WD=Q213263}} (for details as a shikinaisha, see {{ill|lt=Ono Shrine (Tama)#History of shikinaisha “Ono Shrine”|Q11464224|WD=Q11464224}}). Because this shrine is below the {{ill|lt=hake escarpment|Q11275384|WD=Q11275384}}, it is said there came to be two shrines due to relocations caused by flooding of the {{ill|lt=Tama River|Q1063006|WD=Q1063006}}; another view says one is the original shrine and the other a branch.

While Ono Shrine in Tama was protected by the {{ill|lt=Edo shogunate|Q205662|WD=Q205662}} as the {{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q1656379|WD=Q1656379}} of Musashi Province, this shrine declined as reverence increased for nearby Musashi provincial {{ill|lt=sōsha|Q1107129|WD=Q1107129}}, Rokusho-no-miya ({{ill|lt=Ōkunitama Shrine|Q611678|WD=Q611678}}).

In {{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757}} (Meiji 6) it was ranked as gōsha. The shrine burned in a fire in Taishō 15, and the current buildings were rebuilt afterward.

=== Enshrined deities ===
Main deities are the following two.
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ame-no-Shitaharu-no-Mikoto|UNKNOWN}}
* {{ill|lt=Seoritsuhime|Q13579836|WD=Q13579836|lt=Seoritsuhime-no-Mikoto}}

